@startuml seq-link-click-scroll
'' PlantUML over Mermaid because clicking an in-document link is an ordered handshake that (1) is intercepted
'' to stay IN the pane (not window-replace), (2) saves the leaving scroll into per-tab history, and (3)
'' restores the destination scroll after layout. Activation lifetimes + the cofx/fx hops matter, so a
'' PlantUML sequence is the right tool.
!include _vv-theme.iuml

title In-document link click — open in the pane + per-tab scroll restore

autonumber "<b>[0]"

actor User #9F8766
participant "markdown-body\nclick listener" as V #2D9574
participant ":doc/open (reg-event-fx)\n[+ :content-scroll cofx]" as RF #4F97D7
collections "app-db active tab\n:hist [{:uri :scroll}…]" as DB #7590DB
participant "load + render\n(:vv/open → content)" as LOAD #B1951D
participant "scroll restore\n(renderer.scroll)" as SC #4F97D7

== click (the bug fix: open IN the pane) ==
User -> V : click <a href> (a relative .md link)
activate V
V -> V : link/classify(href) → {:kind :file :path}\n.preventDefault — do NOT let Electron replace the window
V -> RF : [:doc/open path]
deactivate V
activate RF
RF -> RF : :content-scroll cofx reads .vv-content scrollTop\n(the position being left behind)
RF -> DB : nav-active — save the leaving :scroll on the current\nentry, push {:uri new :scroll 0}
RF -> LOAD : (fx) load the target document
RF -> SC : (fx) [:scroll/restore 0]  (a new entry → top)
deactivate RF
activate LOAD
LOAD --> V : new :doc/html → markdown-body did-update
deactivate LOAD
activate V
V -> SC : scroll/apply! @node  (next frame + short settle)
activate SC
SC -> V : set .vv-content scrollTop
deactivate SC
deactivate V

== later: Back (Alt+← / mouse button 3) ==
User -> RF : [:history/back]
activate RF
RF -> DB : step −1 — save the leaving scroll,\nreturn [uri, saved-scroll]
RF -> SC : (fx) [:scroll/restore saved-scroll]
deactivate RF

note over DB, SC #FFF6D6
  Each history entry is {:uri :scroll}, so Back restores BOTH the document and
  the exact scroll position it had when you left it. The restore is deferred one
  frame (+ a short settle) so a tall document does not clamp the target against a
  not-yet-complete scroll height. HTTP tabs scroll themselves — no pane restore.
end note

legend right
  |= Colour |= Participant / concept |
  |<#9F8766>| User |
  |<#2D9574>| markdown-body (view) |
  |<#4F97D7>| re-frame event + scroll fx |
  |<#7590DB>| app-db per-tab history {:uri :scroll} |
  |<#B1951D>| load / render the document |
endlegend
@enduml
